    <body>
        <h1 id="Heading">HTML Tables</h1>

        <hr>

        <h2>HTML Tables</h2>
        <p>
            HTML Tables allows the Developer to arrange data into Rows and Columns on the HTML Page formatted as a <b>Table.</b>
        </p>

        
        <table style="width: 70%">
            <caption><b>Sample Table 1</b></caption>

            <tr>
                <th>Country</th>
                <th>Capital</th>
                <th>Continent</th>
            </tr>

            <tr>
                <td>India</td>
                <td>New Delhi</td>
                <td>Asia</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
                <td>Italy</td>
                <td>Rome</td>
                <td>Europe</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
                <td>South Africa</td>
                <td>Cape Town</td>
                <td>Africa</td>
            </tr>
        </table>
        <hr>

        <h2>Table Contents</h2>
        <p>
            Each Cell is defined by the <b>&lt;td&gt;</b> Tag.<br>
            Each Row is defined by the <b>&lt;tr&gt;</b> Tag.<br>
            Table Headers are defined by the <b>&lt;th&gt;</b> Tag.<br>
            Table Caption can be set with the <b>&lt;caption&gt;</b> Tag.<br>
        </p>
        <hr>

        <h2>Table Borders</h2>
        <p>
            The Table itself, the Header Cells and the Content Cells all have individual borders.<br>
            All three of them can have their CSS declared individually with unique attributes like Borders and Background colours.
        </p>

        <p>
            The <b>Border Color</b> Attribute sets the Border Colour.<br>
            The <b>Border Style</b> Attribute sets the Border Style.
        </p>
        <hr>

        <h2>Table Sizes</h2>
        <p>
            The <b>Width</b> Attribute in Percentage declares the relative Width occupied by the table with respect to the body.<br>
            The <b>Width</b> Attribute for a given Header Cell declares the Width occupied by the entire row or Column.<br>
            The <b>Height</b> Attribute for a given row in Pixels declares the Height of the Row.
        </p>
        <hr>

        <h2>Table Headers</h2>
        <p>
            Table Headers can be initialised as both Column headers or row headers usign the &lt;th&gt; tag.<br>
            Table Headers can also span over several Columns using the &lt;colspan&gt; Tag and over several Rows using the &lt;rowspan&lt; Tag<br>
        </p>

        <p>
            The <b>Table Caption</b> is a heading given to the table declared via &lt;caption&gt; Tag.
        </p>
        <hr>

        <h2>Table Padding and Spacing</h2>
        <p>
            The Cells of HTML Table have Padding which is set to 0px by default which can be changed by the <b>Padding</b> Property.<br>
            The Cell Spacing between the Cells is set to 2px by default and can be changed with the <b>Border Spacing</b> Property.
        </p>
        <hr>

        <h2>Table Styling</h2>
        <p>
            A given Row or column or Cell can be styled with a Hover Colour using the <b>Hover</b> property in the CSS.<br>
            Alternate Rows or Columns can be individually Styled using the <b>:nth-child(even)</b> tag in the CSS.<br>
            The &lt;colgroup&gt; tag can be used to address a group of columns seperately in CSS.
        </p>
        <hr>

        <table style="width: 70%">
            <caption><b>Sample Table 2</b></caption>

            <tr>
                <th></th>
                <th>Country</th>
                <th>Capital</th>
                <th>Continent</th>
            </tr>

            <tr>
                <th>1</th>
                <td>India</td>
                <td>New Delhi</td>
                <td>Asia</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
                <th>2</th>
                <td>Italy</td>
                <td>Rome</td>
                <td>Europe</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
                <th rowspan="3">3</th>
                <td rowspan="3">South Africa</td>
                <td>Cape Town</td>
                <td rowspan="3">Africa</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
                <td>Pretoria</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
                <td>Bloemfontein</td>
            </tr>
        </table>


